InSite
The site of InSight
A fixed field console for relational media, designed for designers.

Overview
InSite is a small, self-contained media console built around a single fixed 2D field. Instead of running programs, it hosts relations: cards bend the field, the clock sweeps it, and designers read and intervene in the resulting patterns.

This proposal outlines an incubator-friendly path for developing InSite with InSight: first as an emulator for exploration and visual design, then as a physical controller, and finally as a dedicated hardware console.

What InSite Is
A console, not a stack
InSite is a coordinate-native execution field, canonically a 19 × 19 grid. Every coordinate is meaningful: identity, address, and discrete value collapse into position.

There is no operating system, no window manager, no file hierarchy. There is a field, a structural refresh, and removable cards that define how relations flow.

One field, one function, one wave, one clock
The core design law is extreme simplicity of parts for extreme depth of whole:

One field: a single fixed grid as the only execution space.
One function: one global relational update regime.
One wave: a structured sweep across the field.
One clock: time is the sweep itself, not an abstract timer.
Everything interesting happens inside that constraint.

Cards, Slots, and the Field
Cards as behaviour shards
InSite uses SD cards, but not as file storage. Each card is a behaviour shard:

Relational constraints and transformation tendencies.
Intensity mappings derived from position and relation.
Interpretations of local patterns as "particles" or motifs.
A card does not contain a game, a brush set, or a song. It defines how the field can behave.

Slots as context
InSite treats slots as part of the language, not empty plumbing. The same card in a different slot behaves differently because slot position acts as a contextual transform on the rules.

The active system state is not a single program but a configuration:

field + card A @ slot 1 + card B @ slot 2 + card C @ slot 3 → emergent executable field

A "game", "book", "instrument", or "editor" is a particular card configuration and reading of that field.

Why This Belongs at InSight
A console for graphic thinking
InSite is built for visual and spatial thinkers. Designers can literally place behaviour on a grid, watch it traverse and deform, and treat the resulting patterns as typography, layout, animation, or diagram.

It is a tool for exploring repetition, interference, and asymmetry, all inside a finite, legible field.

InSite as the site of InSight
The console is the site: the place where structure, traversal, and interference happen. The working name deliberately matches InSight's practice:

InSite: the concrete field, the working surface.
InSight: the design practice that reads, shapes, and extends what appears on that field.
The incubator becomes a place where design and computation meet on equal terms.

Proposed Timeline
Phase 1 — Fantasy console (emulation)
Build an InSite emulator: a desktop application that implements the 19 × 19 field, card slots, sweep patterns, and controller injections in software. This is where InSight's designers can start playing: defining card sets, designing visualizations, and exploring what kinds of layouts, animations, and interactive pieces emerge.

Phase 2 — Hardware controller
Develop a modular physical controller for the emulator: knobs, sliders, pads, maybe a small track surface. The controller does not send commands like "move" or "play"; it injects relations into the field: biases, links, and deformations. The goal is to make asymmetry and intervention tactile.

Phase 3 — Dedicated InSite console
Move the field into hardware: a PCB-based console with SD-card slots and a built-in display. At this stage, InSite becomes a standalone object in the studio: designers can plug in behaviour shards, manipulate the field via the controller, and capture stills or sequences as raw material for client work, type experiments, identities, and installations.

Creative Use Cases for InSight
Systems-driven identity
Use InSite fields as the engine behind living logos and identity systems: a set of cards and sweep patterns defines a brand's behaviour, not just its static mark.

Typographic instruments
Treat the grid as a typographic space. Cards define letter behaviour; the controller becomes a way to "play" type structures over time.

Exhibition and installation
Use the hardware console as a gallery object: visitors manipulate InSite directly, generating patterns that can be printed, projected, or woven into other media.

Why an Incubator, Not a Product Brief
InSite is deliberately small in surface and deep in behaviour. It sits in between fields: computation, graphic design, interaction, and instrument building. An incubator is the right frame because the project needs a studio that is comfortable living in those overlaps.

InSight brings one crucial thing that a pure engineering shop does not: a practiced sensitivity to form, rhythm, composition, and client-facing storytelling. InSite offers a new substrate; InSight can help turn it into a usable, communicable tool.

Closing Thought
InSite is a console, not a stack; a field, not a feed. It does not run apps. It hosts relations. The proposal is simple: build a small, legible machine whose job is to let patterns of asymmetry appear, and then let designers at InSight turn those patterns into work.

InSite — a field console proposal for InSight’s incubator.